children.subject: To add, I just finished taking 170. The book is great for understanding the material needed for the course. Start with 0, skip 1, finish the rest of the book then return to 1; that is the order we went over everything last semester.

The coverage of chapter 1 has been in quite a bit of flux over the last few years. It used to be taught like normal (hence why it's in the textbook), and then has been slowly cut away (since it's mostly redundant with 70), with some semesters bringing the non-70 bits (randomized algorithms / hashing parts) as special topics.

For 170 -- the textbook we use is Algorithms by Dasgupta, Papadimitriou and Vazirani. There are no practice problem sets (and looking at past semesters' homeworks and solutions is against course policy.) Lecture webcasts are available from previous semesters on webcast.berkeley.edu.

history.content: For 126, just make sure you are comfortable with probability at the CS 70 level. For the first part of the course we will use the textbook Introduction to Probability by Bertsekas and Tsitsiklis, which is well-written. The first 3 chapters or so mostly cover material that is familiar from CS 70, so if you would like to get some practice done, you could work out some of the problems there.
